Week 14 IP: Assosiation Analysis

1.Defining the Question

Specifying the Data Analytic Question

Create association rules that will allow for identification of relationships between items given a dataset that comprises groups of items from Carrefour supermarkets.

Defining the Metrics for success

This study will be considered successful if:

  • relationships between the items are identified and are clearly explained
  • insights are drawn from the relationships and recommendations are given

Understanding the context

Identifying relationships between items is an important aspect in todays retail environments as theres a growing trend in customers expecting the sellers to tell what they might want to buy. If sellers can tell the customers what they might want to buy it not only improves their sales, but also the customer experience and ultimately life time value.

**Why is this study relevant?*

As a Data Scientist of Carrefour Kenya, this study will help inform the marketing team on which items should be placed together in the stores and in what aisles. This will assist the team to come up with the most relevant marketing strategies that will result in the highest no. of sales. At large, this study will help come up with a more detailed explanation of how to make business decisions in retail environments.

With a support of only 0.002 and a confidence of 0.08, we get a total of only 2 rules while reducing the support to 0.6 outputs a total of 545 rules. The first set has a very little rules while the second set has too many hence we shall tune these parameters to get a reasonable number of rules

5.Visualizations

#scatter plot with support on the x-axis and lift on the y-axis
#the intensity of the items shows the confidence of that rule
plot(rules4, measure = c("support", "lift"), shading = "confidence", jitter = 0)

Items with high confidence have an equally high lift while the support does not really influence the confidence

# plotting a two key plot with support on the x-axis and confidence on the y-axis 
# the color of the points is used to indicate order, i.e the number of items contained in the rule.
plot(rules4, method = "two-key plot", jitter = 0)

From the plot above, we can see that most of the rules contained 4 items while just one observation contains 6 items
